ash;17)<ref>[http://www.holyspirithighschool.com/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=280495&type=d&pREC_ID=635961 Tuition Information], Holy Spirit High School. Accessed January 17, 2017.</ref>\n| endowment         = \n| grades            = [[Ninth grade|9]]\u2013[[Twelfth grade|12]]\n| campus            = \n| campus size       = \n| campus type       = \n| athletics         = \n| conference        = [[Cape-Atlantic League]]\n| slogan            = \n| song              = \n| fightsong         = \n| motto             = ''Caritas Omnia Vincit''\n| motto_translation = Love conquers all things\n| accreditation     = [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools]]<ref name=MSA-CSS/>\n| rival             = \n| mascot            = \n| mascot image      = \n| sports            = \n| patron            = \n| teamname          = Spartans<ref name=NJSIAAprofile/>\n| nickname          = \n| colors            = {{Color box|Navy blue}} Navy blue and<br>{{Color box|#C5B358}} Vegas gold<ref name=NJSIAAprofile/>\n| yearbook          = \n| publication       = \n| newspaper         = \n| established       = 1922\n| status            = \n| closed            = \n| alumni            = \n| nobel_laureates   =\n| enrollment        = 380 (as of 2015-16)<ref name=NCES/>\n| faculty           = 32.1 [[full-time equivalent|FTEs]]<ref name=NCES/>\n| ratio             = 11.8:1<ref name=NCES/>\n| grade9            = \n| grade10           = \n| grade11           = \n| grade12           = \n| other_grade_label = \n| other             = \n| communities       = \n| feeders           = \n| free_label        = \n| free_text         = \n| free_label1       = \n| free_text1        = \n| free_label2       = \n| free_text2        = \n| free_label3       = Athletic Director\n| free_text3        = Steve Normane\n| free_label4       = \n| free_text4        = \n| free_label5       = \n| free_text5        = \n| footnotes         = \n| picture           = \n| homepage          = [http://holyspirithighschool.com holyspirithighschool.com] \n}}\n'''Holy Spirit High School''' is a [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] [[University-preparatory school|preparatory school]] located in [[Absecon, New Jersey]], just outside [[Atlantic City, New Jersey|Atlantic City]]. The school is under the jurisdiction of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Camden|Diocese of Camden]].<ref>[http://www.camdendiocese.org/schools/catholic-schools-listing/ Catholic Schools Directory], [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Camden]]. Accessed October 20, 2016.</ref> The school's [[motto]] is ''Caritas Omnia Vincit'' &ndash; which translates to 'love conquers all things'. The school has been accredited by the [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools]] Commission on Secondary Schools since 1971.<ref name=MSA-CSS>[https://www.msa-cess.org/RelId/606553/AccountID/12176/ISvars/default/School_Search.htm Holy Spirit High School], [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools]] Commission on Secondary Schools. Accessed December 9, 2019.</ref>\n\nAs of the 2015-16 school year, the school had an enrollment of 380 students and 32.1 classroom teachers (on an [[full-time equivalent|FTE]] basis), for a [[student\u2013teacher ratio]] of 11.8:1. The school's student body was 78.2% White, 6.8% Black, 6.8% Hispanic, 5.0% Asian and 3.2% two or more races.<ref name=NCES>[https://nces.ed.gov/surveys/pss/privateschoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&ID=00864978 School data for Holy Spirit High School], [[National Center for Education Statistics]]. Accessed October 20, 2017.</ref>\n\nThe school is under the limited governance of an independent Board of Trustees. The Bishop of Camden is responsible for the proper teaching of the Catholic faith, the proper celebration of the sacraments and the overall Catholic identity of the institution. The President/Principal serves as the Chairman of the Board of Trustees and the chief administrative officer of Holy Spirit High School.\n\n==Athletics==\nThe Holy Spirit High School Spartans<ref name=NJSIAAprofile>[http://www.njsiaa.org/holy-spirit-high-school Holy Spirit High School], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed May 26, 2016.</ref> compete in the National Division of the [[Cape-Atlantic League]], an athletic conference consisting of both parochial and private and public high schools located in Atlantic County, [[Cape May County, New Jersey|Cape May County]], [[Cumberland County, New Jersey|Cumberland County]], and [[Gloucester County, New Jersey|Gloucester County]]. The Cape-Atlantic League operates under the aegis of the [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]].<ref>[http://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/Schools%20by%20Conference%202016-2017.pdf League & Conference Affiliations] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109010028/http://www.njsiaa.org/NJSIAA/12leagueaffiliations.pdf |date=2012-11-09 }}, [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed January 9, 2017.</ref> The football team competes in the United Division of the 95-team [[West Jersey Football League]] superconference<ref>[http://www.westjerseyfootball.com/divisions.html Divisions], West Jersey Football League. Accessed September 25, 2017.</ref> and was classified by the NJSIAA as Non-Public Group II for football for 2017-18.<ref>[http://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/Football%20classifications%20%2717-%2718_0.pdf NJSIAA Football Public School Classifications 2017-2018] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926143103/http://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/Football%20classifications%20'17-'18_0.pdf |date=2017-09-26 }}, [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]], finalized August 2, 2017. Accessed September 25, 2017.</ref>\n\nThe football team won the Non-Public A South state sectional championships in 1974, 1975 and 1978. The 1987 football team won the Parochial A state title by defeating Notre Dame High School 15\u20138. The 2007 team held an undefeated record of 12-0 and won the Non-Public, Group III state sectional championship with a 26\u201313 win over [[Immaculata High School (New Jersey)|Immaculata High School]]. The undefeated season and state championship were both firsts in team history.<ref>[http://www.bracketmaker.com/tmenu.cfm?tid=246272&tclass=Non%2DPublic%2C%20Group%20III 2007 Football - Non-Public, Group III], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed December 23, 2007.</ref><ref>McGarry, Michael. [http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/sports/highschool/story/7520113p-7420027c.html \"Defense leads Holy Spirit to first football state title\"], ''[[The Press of Atlantic City]]'', December 2, 2007. Accessed December 23, 2007. \"It is the first state title in Holy Spirit football history. Spirit's victory ended Immaculata's 23-game winning streak. Spirit finishes 12-0 for the first time in school history.\"</ref> The 2010 team won the Non-Public Group III state title, and the 2011 and 2012 teams won the Non-Public Group II championships.<ref>Goldberg, Jeff. [http://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/15%20History%20of%20Football.pdf NJSIAA Football Playoff Champions], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed November 19, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn the 1970s through the late 1980s, Holy Spirit made a name for itself in boys' rowing, winning several national championships and competing several times at the [[Henley Royal Regatta|Henley Regatta]] on the [[River Thames]] by the town of [[Henley-on-Thames]], [[England]].<ref>Wilkins, Joseph T. [http://www.brigantinerowingclub.org/Misc_home/BRCHist.html A Short History of the Brigantine Rowing Club] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070821115940/http://www.brigantinerowingclub.org/Misc_home/BRCHist.html |date=2007-08-21 }}. Accessed July 17, 2007.</ref>  This rowing success led to an entry in ''[[The Official Preppy Handbook]]'' in 1980. The boys' rowing team has competed for the [[Princess Elizabeth Challenge Cup]] at Henley six times 1970, 1974, 1976, 1981, 1982, and 2003. The team won in 1974, 1976, and 1981; in addition to finishing second twice, in a race in which the winner is widely considered to be the best youth crew in the world. Holy Spirit's three titles is tied with [[St. Paul's School (Concord, New Hampshire)|St. Paul's School]] for the most by any American high school.<ref>[http://www.rowinghistory.net/HRR%20US/hrr_1946-2000.htm Results of Final Races - 1946-2003] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716161931/http://www.rowinghistory.net/HRR%20US/hrr_1946-2000.htm |date=2011-07-16 }}, [[Henley Royal Regatta]]. Accessed July 10, 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.rowinghistory.net/HRR US/HRR-US frame.htm U.S. Winners]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[Henley Royal Regatta]]. Accessed July 10, 2011.</ref> Coach Stan Bergman led the team to all three Henley victories.\n\nThe girls eight-person rowing team won the Peabody Cup at the 2003 [[Henley Women's Regatta]], defeating the Kingston School of England. Their coach, Joseph Welsh Jr., was a member of the boys team at Holy Spirit when it won a similar championship at Henley in 1976.<ref>Strauss, Robert. [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F04E7DF143AF93AA15755C0A9659C8B63 \"WORTH NOTING; Sailing, Sailing, To a Girls' Championship\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', June 29, 2003. Accessed October 25, 2007. \"Last Sunday, the girls varsity rowing team from Holy Spirit High School, in Absecon, won the Peabody Cup, the top prize in the school/junior category in the Henley Women's Regatta at Henley-on-Thames, England. Though not officially so, the regatta is considered the world championships of rowing, and the Peabody Cup thus gives the Holy Spirit Panthers bragging rights as the best high school eight-person rowing team in the world.\"</ref> The girls eight-person rowing team repeated the win of the Peabody Cup at the 2004 Henley Women's Regatta; this time defeating a fellow US team, [[St. Andrew's School (Delaware)|St. Andrew's School]] of Delaware.<ref>Staff. [http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AC&p_theme=ac&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1035F0CAF76CE435&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM \"Holy Spirit Rows to a Repeat\"], ''[[The Press of Atlantic City]]'', June 21, 2004. Accessed July 10, 2011. \"The Holy Spirit High School girls varsity-eight crew celebrates repeating as Peabody Cup champion at the Henley Women's Regatta in Henley-on-Thames, England, on Sunday.\"</ref>\n\nThe field hockey team won the Parochial A South state sectional championships in 1982.<ref>[http://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/Field%20Hockey%20Program-TofC%202015.pdf History of the NJSIAA Field Hockey Championships], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed December 5, 2015.</ref>\n\nThe 2005 softball team won the Non-Public, South B state sectional championship with a 10\u20136 win over [[St. Joseph High School (Hammonton, New Jersey)|St. Joseph High School]] in the tournament final.<ref>[http://www.bracketmaker.com/tmenu.cfm?tid=107416&tclass=Non-Public%2C%20South%20B 2005 Softball - Non-Public, South B], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 17, 2007.</ref>\n\nThe boys' swimming team won the Non-Public A state championship in 2000 and 2001 and the Non-Public B state championship in 2002, 2003, 2005 and 2006. The 2006 title came in a 95.5\u201374.5 tournament win over [[Bishop Eustace High School]].<ref>Gargan, Guy. [http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AC&p_theme=ac&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1100FB07614A2010&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM \"High School Swimming Championship: Deep Spirit Rules State\"], ''[[The Press of Atlantic City]]'', February 26, 2006. Accessed July 10, 2011. \"The Holy Spirit High School boys swimming team had fewer first-place finishes than Bishop Eustace Prep on Saturday in their state Non-Public B championship meet, but the Spartans kept pulling away. Kevin Cain's wins in the 100-yard butterfly and the 100 backstroke led Holy Spirit to a 95.5-74.5 victory at The College of New Jersey.\"</ref>\n\nThe girls' swimming team won the Non Public A state championship in 2007 with a 102\u201368 win against [[Red Bank Catholic High School]].<ref>[http://www.bracketmaker.com/tmenu.cfm?tid=201923&tclass=Non%20Public%20-%20%20A 2007 Girls Team Swimming - Non Public - A], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 22, 2007.</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the boys' basketball team brought home the school's first Cape Atlantic League championship after defeating their rival [[Atlantic City High School]], finishing the season with a record of 26-3.<ref>Burrows, Walt. [https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courierpostonline/access/1771204291.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+26%2C+2006&author=WALT+BURROWS&pub=Courier+Post&desc=Spiller's+tip-in+lifts+Holy+Spirit&pqatl=google \"Spiller's tip-in lifts Holy Spirit\"], ''[[Courier-Post]]'', February 26, 2006. Accessed July 10, 2011. \"Cliff Spiller was in an unfamiliar role Saturday when he scored the winning basket and finished with a career-high 13 points in leading Holy Spirit High School to its first-ever Cape-Atlantic League overall boys' basketball championship. \"</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the girls' soccer team won their first Cape Atlantic League championship, beating [[Ocean City High School]] 4\u20131, after having lost in the league's title game in each of the four previous years.<ref>McCann, Courtney. [http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AC&p_theme=ac&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1062730792DD7EE8&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM \"Girls High School Soccer Cape Atlantic League Championships / Spirit Upsets Ocean City\"], ''[[The Press of Atlantic City]]'', November 3, 2004. Accessed September 10, 2012. \"It may have taken four years, but the Holy Spirit High School girls soccer team finally got what it came for. The Spartans upset Ocean City 4-1 to win the Cape-Atlantic League Championship on Tuesday.\"</ref>\n\nThe 2007 girls' tennis team took the South A state sectional championship with a 3\u20132 win over [[Notre Dame High School (New Jersey)|Notre Dame High School]] in the tournament final.<ref>[http://www.bracketmaker.com/tmenu.cfm?tid=242871&tclass=South%20A 2007 Girls Team Tennis - South A], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed October 26, 2007.</ref>\n\nThe baseball team finished the season with a 14\u201316 record, winning the South Jersey Non-Public final by a score of 7\u20131 against [[Marist High School (New Jersey)|Marist High School]] and then won the Non-Public B state championship for the first time since 1982 with a 9\u20134 win against [[Newark Academy]].<ref>McGarry, Michael. [http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/sports/local/highschool/holy-spirit-baseball-wins-first-state-title-in-years/article_894f41de-0c8c-11e5-96ce-5f4c9ef305e0.html \"Holy Spirit baseball wins first state title in 33 years\"], ''[[The Press of Atlantic City]]'', June 6, 2015. Accessed May 26, 2016. \"The Spartans capped their memorable playoff run by beating Newark Academy 9-4 to win the state Non-Public B title at Toms River North on Saturday afternoon.... The win gave Spirit its first state baseball title since 1982..\"</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the girls' soccer team won the South Jersey Non-Public B final against [[Our Lady of Mercy Academy (New Jersey)|Our Lady of Mercy Academy]] 4\u20131 after losing the previous year to Moorestown Friends. This was the first time Spartan girls' soccer has won this title and the first time the team went to the New Jersey Non-Public B state final.<ref>Gould, Brandon. [http://highschoolsports.nj.com/news/article/-4582336301425343878/girls-soccer-2016-non-public-b-state-final-preview-holy-spirit-vs-morris-catholic/ \"Girls Soccer: 2016 Non-Public B final preview - Holy Spirit vs. Morris Catholic\"], NJ Advance Media for [[NJ.com]], November 11, 2016. Accessed January 10, 2017. \"Holy Spirit made school history on Thursday with a 4-1 victory over Our Lady of Mercy in the South Jersey, Non-Public B final. Christine Conaghy scored three times in the final to lift the fifth-seeded South Jersey squad to its first ever sectional title.\"</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\nDevon Parto - crackhead\n{{Category see also|Holy Spirit High School alumni}}\n* [[Joe Callahan (American football)|Joe Callahan]] (born 1993), football quarterback who played for the [[Green Bay Packers]].<ref>Clements, Ron. [http://www.sportingnews.com/nfl/news/joe-callahan-green-bay-rookie-quarterback-hall-of-fame-game/cyylqey8s8gg1s0kkxjhv4mgt \"Who is Joe Callahan? Get to know the Packers rookie QB\"], ''[[Sporting News]]'', August 7, 2016. Accessed October 2, 2017. \"Callahan, whose full name is Francis Joseph, was born and raised in Absecon, N.J., where he was a standout player at Holy Spirit High School.\"</ref>\n* [[John F. Duffy]] (born 1963), legal commentator and author, Professor of Law at the [[University of Virginia School of Law]].{{citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n* [[Chris Ford]] (born 1949), pro-basketball player, head coach.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=1731658 \"Assistant Ford promoted to replace Ayers\"], [[ESPN.com]], February 10, 2004. Accessed May 21, 2007. \"A native of Atlantic City, N.J., Ford attended Holy Spirit High School in Absecon, N.J., and went on to play at Villanova University from 1968-72, where he helped the Wildcats reach the 1971 NCAA championship game against UCLA.\"</ref>\n* [[William Green (American football)|William Green]] (born 1979), [[running back]] who currently is a [[free agent]] of the [[National Football League|NFL]].<ref>[http://www.nflplayers.com/players/player.aspx?id=32992 William Green player profile], [[National Football League Players Association]]. Accessed July 23, 2007. \"Hometown: Atlantic City, NJ... Earned All-America honors from Super Prep, Tom Lemming, National Recruiting Advisor, RivalNet, Prep Star, Parade and Blue Chip Illustrated and was rated among Super Prep's National Top 50 (third-rated running back on the magazine's dream team), in addition to being a consensus all-state selection at Holy Spirit (Atlantic City, N.J.) High School.\"</ref>\n* [[Dennis Horner]] (born 1988), basketball player who played for the [[NBA]]'s [[New Jersey Nets]].<ref>[http://www.nj.com/nets/index.ssf/2011/12/nets_finalize_roster_by_waivin.html Nets finalize roster by waiving Ime Udoka, keeping Linwood native Dennis Horner] By Jorge Castillo, The Star-Ledger of Newark, December 23, 2011</ref>\n* [[Brian Joo]] (born 1981), of [[Fly to the Sky]], American R&B and South Korean pop (a.k.a. K-pop) recording artist and entertainer who is based in the United States and South Korea.<ref>Eisenlohr, Scott. [http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AC&p_theme=ac&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=10E1FF72DB35E1A0&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM \"Don't Stop the Music: Holy Spirit Music Department Needs a Hand\"], ''[[The Press of Atlantic City]]'', November 23, 2005. Accessed October 24, 2011. \"Brian Joo, 1999, achieved stardom in the Asian community with the group 'Fly to the Sky,' and has three albums to his credit.\"</ref>\n* [[Phil Leonetti]] (born 1953), former Philadelphia crime family [[underboss]]<ref>Anastasia, George. [http://www.jerseymanmagazine.com/mobscene-leonetti.php \"Mobscene.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407092019/http://www.jerseymanmagazine.com/mobscene-leonetti.php |date=2014-04-07 }}, ''JerseyMan Magazine'', September 17, 2012. Accessed April 5, 2014.</ref>\n* [[Michelle Malkin]] (born 1970), political commentator and author.<ref>[http://goliath.ecnext.com/premium/0199/0199-5264457.html \"Michelle Malkin: as a book author, newspaper columnist, television commentator, and blogger, this young first-generation American has used a pull-no-punches style to criticize U.S. immigration and war-on-terror policies.\"], ''[[The American Enterprise]]'', September 1, 2005. Accessed October 25, 2007. \"After graduating from Holy Spirit High School I went to Oberlin College in Ohio, a small, radically left-wing, liberal arts college.\"</ref>\n* [[Don McGahn]] (born 1968), [[White House Office|White House]] [[White House Counsel|Counsel]] and Assistant to the President for [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Donald Trump]] and a former Commissioner of the United States [[Federal Election Commission]].<ref>DeRosier, John. [http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/news/atlantic-city-native-embroiled-in-trump-flynn-controversy/article_049d529a-fbf9-53d7-82b0-82187a457efe.html \"Atlantic City native embroiled in Trump/Flynn controversy \"], ''[[The Press of Atlantic City]]'', May 17, 2017. Accessed November 15, 2017. \"McGahn, a longtime Republican campaign lawyer and former commissioner at the Federal Election Commission, grew up in Atlantic City, attending Our Lady Star of the Sea school and Holy Spirit High School, where he played football.\"</ref>\n* [[John P. O'Neill]] (1952\u20132001), FBI Terrorist Specialist, Director of Security [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]], died in the [[September 11th, 2001 terrorist attacks]].<ref>Meyer, Josh. [http://articles.latimes.com/2001/sep/29/news/mn-51283 \"Anti-Terrorist Elite Bury Victim of Cause: Colleagues in the battle pause to eulogize John P. O'Neill, killed in the World Trade Center.\"], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', September 29, 2001. Accessed October 24, 2011. \"Within days of graduating from Holy Spirit High School in Atlantic City, O'Neill signed on with the FBI as a fingerprinting clerk. He rose quickly, becoming an agent and holding various field and management positions in Washington, Chicago, Baltimore and New York.\"</ref>\n* [[Greg Roman]] (born 1972), offensive coordinator for the [[Baltimore Ravens]].<ref>Staff.  [http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/sports_hs_football/agent-says-ventnor-native-greg-roman-a-finalist-for-penn/article_b75d8c03-cbf3-563f-9102-b218997d7447.html \"Agent says Ventnor native Greg Roman a finalist for Penn State job\"], ''[[The Press of Atlantic City]]'', January 3, 2012. Accessed September 10, 2012. \"San Francisco 49ers offensive coordinator Greg Roman, a Ventnor native and Holy Spirit High School graduate, is a finalist for the Penn State football head-coaching job, his agent said Monday.\"</ref>\n* [[Nicky Scarfo Jr.]] (born 1964), former [[Philadelphia crime family]] boss and [[Lucchese crime family]] soldier<ref>Anastasia, George. \"'Nicky Jr.': Where Does the Boss' Son Fit In?\" ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'', March 10, 1991.</ref><ref>Anastasia, George. [http://www.philly.com/inquirer/front_page/20071224_Probes_detailed_view_of_mob_life.html \"Probe's Detailed View of Mob Life.\"], ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'', December 24, 2007. Accessed April 12, 2008.</ref>\n* [[Stephanie Williams (Miss District of Columbia)|Stephanie Williams]] (born 1986), [[Miss District of Columbia]] 2010.<ref>Berger, Howard. [http://www.jewishtimes-sj.com/news/2011-04-08/Columns/Honorable_Menschen.html \"Honorable 'Menschen'\"], ''Jewish Times of South Jersey'', April 8, 2011. Accessed October 24, 2011. \"Stephanie Williams, raised in Margate, graduated Holy Spirit HS and Wagner College, and attending George Washington University Medical School was Miss Washington, DC in January's Miss America Pageant in Las Vegas.\"</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://holyspirithighschool.com/ School website]\n*[https://nces.ed.gov/surveys/pss/privateschoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&ID=00864978 Holy Spirit High School], [[National Center for Education Statistics]]\n*[http://www.sjsports.com/highschool/holyspirit/ South Jersey Sports: Holy Spirit HS]\n*[http://classreport.org/usa/nj/absecon/hshs/ Holy Spirit High School Alumni/Reunion Web Site]\n\n{{Atlantic County, New Jersey High Schools}}\n{{Cape-Atlantic League}}\n{{West Jersey Football League}}\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Camden}}\n\n[[Category:1922 establishments in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1922]]\n[[Category:Middle States Commission on Secondary Schools]]\n[[Category:Private high schools in Atlantic County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Diocese of Camden]]\n[[Category:Catholic secondary schools in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Absecon, New Jersey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox School\n| name              = Holy Spirit High School\n| native_name       = \n| latin_name        = \n| image             =<!-- Deleted image removed:  [[File:Image.ashx.jpg]] -->\n| imagesize         = \n| caption           = \n| location          = \n| streetaddress     = 500 South New Road\n| city              = [[Absecon, New Jersey|Absecon]]\n| state             = [[New Jersey|NJ]]\n| county            =\n| zipcode           = 08201\n| country           = United States\n| coordinates       = {{coord|39|25|2|N|74|30|35|W|type:edu_region:US-NJ|display=inline,title}}\n| schoolnumber      = \n| schoolboard       = \n| district          = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Camden|Diocese of Camden]]\n| authority         = \n| religion          = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| denomination      = \n| oversight         = \n| affiliation       = \n| superintendent    = \n| trustee           = \n| founder           = \n| president         = Fr. Perry Cherubini<ref name=Profile>[https://www.holyspirithighschool.com/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=280383&type=d&pREC_ID=635554 School Profile 2019 - 2020], Holy Spirit High School. Accessed December 9, 2019.</ref>\n| principal         = Dr. Thomas J. Farren Sr.<ref name=Profile/>\n| administrator     =  \n| dean              = Dennis Smith<ref name=Profile/>\n| rector            = \n| chaplain          = \n| director          = \n| staff             = \n| ranking           = \n| teaching_staff    = \n| roll              = \n| MOE               = \n| ceeb              = 310025\n| school code       = \n| LEA               = \n| ofsted            = \n| testaverage       = \n| testname          = \n| national_ranking  = \n| avg_class_size    = \n| SAT               = \n| ACT               = \n| type              = [[University-preparatory school|Preparatory School]], [[Coeducational]]\n| system            = \n| fees              = \n| tuition           = $8,550 (2016&ndash;17)<ref>[http://www.holyspirithighschool.com/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=280495&type=d&pREC_ID=635961 Tuition Information], Holy Spirit High School. Accessed January 17, 2017.</ref>\n| endowment         = \n| grades            = [[Ninth grade|9]]\u2013[[Twelfth grade|12]]\n| campus            = \n| campus size       = \n| campus type       = \n| athletics         = \n| conference        = [[Cape-Atlantic League]]\n| slogan            = \n| song              = \n| fightsong         = \n| motto             = ''Caritas Omnia Vincit''\n| motto_translation = Love conquers all things\n| accreditation     = [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools]]<ref name=MSA-CSS/>\n| rival             = \n| mascot            = \n| mascot image      = \n| sports            = \n| patron            = \n| teamname          = Spartans<ref name=NJSIAAprofile/>\n| nickname          = \n| colors            = {{Color box|Navy blue}} Navy blue and<br>{{Color box|#C5B358}} Vegas gold<ref name=NJSIAAprofile/>\n| yearbook          = \n| publication       = \n| newspaper         = \n| established       = 1922\n| status            = \n| closed            = \n| alumni            = \n| nobel_laureates   =\n| enrollment        = 380 (as of 2015-16)<ref name=NCES/>\n| faculty           = 32.1 [[full-time equivalent|FTEs]]<ref name=NCES/>\n| ratio             = 11.8:1<ref name=NCES/>\n| grade9            = \n| grade10           = \n| grade11           = \n| grade12           = \n| other_grade_label = \n| other             = \n| communities       = \n| feeders           = \n| free_label        = \n| free_text         = \n| free_label1       = \n| free_text1        = \n| free_label2       = \n| free_text2        = \n| free_label3       = Athletic Director\n| free_text3        = Steve Normane\n| free_label4       = \n| free_text4        = \n| free_label5       = \n| free_text5        = \n| footnotes         = \n| picture           = \n| homepage          = [http://holyspirithighschool.com holyspirithighschool.com] \n}}\n'''Holy Spirit High School''' is a [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] [[University-preparatory school|preparatory school]] located in [[Absecon, New Jersey]], just outside [[Atlantic City, New Jersey|Atlantic City]]. The school is under the jurisdiction of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Camden|Diocese of Camden]].<ref>[http://www.camdendiocese.org/schools/catholic-schools-listing/ Catholic Schools Directory], [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Camden]]. Accessed October 20, 2016.</ref> The school's [[motto]] is ''Caritas Omnia Vincit'' &ndash; which translates to 'love conquers all things'. The school has been accredited by the [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools]] Commission on Secondary Schools since 1971.<ref name=MSA-CSS>[https://www.msa-cess.org/RelId/606553/AccountID/12176/ISvars/default/School_Search.htm Holy Spirit High School], [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools]] Commission on Secondary Schools. Accessed December 9, 2019.</ref>\n\nAs of the 2015-16 school year, the school had an enrollment of 380 students and 32.1 classroom teachers (on an [[full-time equivalent|FTE]] basis), for a [[student\u2013teacher ratio]] of 11.8:1. The school's student body was 78.2% White, 6.8% Black, 6.8% Hispanic, 5.0% Asian and 3.2% two or more races.<ref name=NCES>[https://nces.ed.gov/surveys/pss/privateschoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&ID=00864978 School data for Holy Spirit High School], [[National Center for Education Statistics]]. Accessed October 20, 2017.</ref>\n\nThe school is under the limited governance of an independent Board of Trustees. The Bishop of Camden is responsible for the proper teaching of the Catholic faith, the proper celebration of the sacraments and the overall Catholic identity of the institution. The President/Principal serves as the Chairman of the Board of Trustees and the chief administrative officer of Holy Spirit High School.\n\n==Athletics==\nThe Holy Spirit High School Spartans<ref name=NJSIAAprofile>[http://www.njsiaa.org/holy-spirit-high-school Holy Spirit High School], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed May 26, 2016.</ref> compete in the National Division of the [[Cape-Atlantic League]], an athletic conference consisting of both parochial and private and public high schools located in Atlantic County, [[Cape May County, New Jersey|Cape May County]], [[Cumberland County, New Jersey|Cumberland County]], and [[Gloucester County, New Jersey|Gloucester County]]. The Cape-Atlantic League operates under the aegis of the [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]].<ref>[http://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/Schools%20by%20Conference%202016-2017.pdf League & Conference Affiliations] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109010028/http://www.njsiaa.org/NJSIAA/12leagueaffiliations.pdf |date=2012-11-09 }}, [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed January 9, 2017.</ref> The football team competes in the United Division of the 95-team [[West Jersey Football League]] superconference<ref>[http://www.westjerseyfootball.com/divisions.html Divisions], West Jersey Football League. Accessed September 25, 2017.</ref> and was classified by the NJSIAA as Non-Public Group II for football for 2017-18.<ref>[http://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/Football%20classifications%20%2717-%2718_0.pdf NJSIAA Football Public School Classifications 2017-2018] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926143103/http://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/Football%20classifications%20'17-'18_0.pdf |date=2017-09-26 }}, [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]], finalized August 2, 2017. Accessed September 25, 2017.</ref>\n\nThe football team won the Non-Public A South state sectional championships in 1974, 1975 and 1978. The 1987 football team won the Parochial A state title by defeating Notre Dame High School 15\u20138. The 2007 team held an undefeated record of 12-0 and won the Non-Public, Group III state sectional championship with a 26\u201313 win over [[Immaculata High School (New Jersey)|Immaculata High School]]. The undefeated season and state championship were both firsts in team history.<ref>[http://www.bracketmaker.com/tmenu.cfm?tid=246272&tclass=Non%2DPublic%2C%20Group%20III 2007 Football - Non-Public, Group III], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed December 23, 2007.</ref><ref>McGarry, Michael. [http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/sports/highschool/story/7520113p-7420027c.html \"Defense leads Holy Spirit to first football state title\"], ''[[The Press of Atlantic City]]'', December 2, 2007. Accessed December 23, 2007. \"It is the first state title in Holy Spirit football history. Spirit's victory ended Immaculata's 23-game winning streak. Spirit finishes 12-0 for the first time in school history.\"</ref> The 2010 team won the Non-Public Group III state title, and the 2011 and 2012 teams won the Non-Public Group II championships.<ref>Goldberg, Jeff. [http://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/15%20History%20of%20Football.pdf NJSIAA Football Playoff Champions], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed November 19, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn the 1970s through the late 1980s, Holy Spirit made a name for itself in boys' rowing, winning several national championships and competing several times at the [[Henley Royal Regatta|Henley Regatta]] on the [[River Thames]] by the town of [[Henley-on-Thames]], [[England]].<ref>Wilkins, Joseph T. [http://www.brigantinerowingclub.org/Misc_home/BRCHist.html A Short History of the Brigantine Rowing Club] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070821115940/http://www.brigantinerowingclub.org/Misc_home/BRCHist.html |date=2007-08-21 }}. Accessed July 17, 2007.</ref>  This rowing success led to an entry in ''[[The Official Preppy Handbook]]'' in 1980. The boys' rowing team has competed for the [[Princess Elizabeth Challenge Cup]] at Henley six times 1970, 1974, 1976, 1981, 1982, and 2003. The team won in 1974, 1976, and 1981; in addition to finishing second twice, in a race in which the winner is widely considered to be the best youth crew in the world. Holy Spirit's three titles is tied with [[St. Paul's School (Concord, New Hampshire)|St. Paul's School]] for the most by any American high school.<ref>[http://www.rowinghistory.net/HRR%20US/hrr_1946-2000.htm Results of Final Races - 1946-2003] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716161931/http://www.rowinghistory.net/HRR%20US/hrr_1946-2000.htm |date=2011-07-16 }}, [[Henley Royal Regatta]]. Accessed July 10, 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.rowinghistory.net/HRR US/HRR-US frame.htm U.S. Winners]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[Henley Royal Regatta]]. Accessed July 10, 2011.</ref> Coach Stan Bergman led the team to all three Henley victories.\n\nThe girls eight-person rowing team won the Peabody Cup at the 2003 [[Henley Women's Regatta]], defeating the Kingston School of England. Their coach, Joseph Welsh Jr., was a member of the boys team at Holy Spirit when it won a similar championship at Henley in 1976.<ref>Strauss, Robert. [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F04E7DF143AF93AA15755C0A9659C8B63 \"WORTH NOTING; Sailing, Sailing, To a Girls' Championship\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', June 29, 2003. Accessed October 25, 2007. \"Last Sunday, the girls varsity rowing team from Holy Spirit High School, in Absecon, won the Peabody Cup, the top prize in the school/junior category in the Henley Women's Regatta at Henley-on-Thames, England. Though not officially so, the regatta is considered the world championships of rowing, and the Peabody Cup thus gives the Holy Spirit Panthers bragging rights as the best high school eight-person rowing team in the world.\"</ref> The girls eight-person rowing team repeated the win of the Peabody Cup at the 2004 Henley Women's Regatta; this time defeating a fellow US team, [[St. Andrew's School (Delaware)|St. Andrew's School]] of Delaware.<ref>Staff. [http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AC&p_theme=ac&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1035F0CAF76CE435&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM \"Holy Spirit Rows to a Repeat\"], ''[[The Press of Atlantic City]]'', June 21, 2004. Accessed July 10, 2011. \"The Holy Spirit High School girls varsity-eight crew celebrates repeating as Peabody Cup champion at the Henley Women's Regatta in Henley-on-Thames, England, on Sunday.\"</ref>\n\nThe field hockey team won the Parochial A South state sectional championships in 1982.<ref>[http://www.njsiaa.org/sites/default/files/document/Field%20Hockey%20Program-TofC%202015.pdf History of the NJSIAA Field Hockey Championships], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed December 5, 2015.</ref>\n\nThe 2005 softball team won the Non-Public, South B state sectional championship with a 10\u20136 win over [[St. Joseph High School (Hammonton, New Jersey)|St. Joseph High School]] in the tournament final.<ref>[http://www.bracketmaker.com/tmenu.cfm?tid=107416&tclass=Non-Public%2C%20South%20B 2005 Softball - Non-Public, South B], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 17, 2007.</ref>\n\nThe boys' swimming team won the Non-Public A state championship in 2000 and 2001 and the Non-Public B state championship in 2002, 2003, 2005 and 2006. The 2006 title came in a 95.5\u201374.5 tournament win over [[Bishop Eustace High School]].<ref>Gargan, Guy. [http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AC&p_theme=ac&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1100FB07614A2010&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM \"High School Swimming Championship: Deep Spirit Rules State\"], ''[[The Press of Atlantic City]]'', February 26, 2006. Accessed July 10, 2011. \"The Holy Spirit High School boys swimming team had fewer first-place finishes than Bishop Eustace Prep on Saturday in their state Non-Public B championship meet, but the Spartans kept pulling away. Kevin Cain's wins in the 100-yard butterfly and the 100 backstroke led Holy Spirit to a 95.5-74.5 victory at The College of New Jersey.\"</ref>\n\nThe girls' swimming team won the Non Public A state championship in 2007 with a 102\u201368 win against [[Red Bank Catholic High School]].<ref>[http://www.bracketmaker.com/tmenu.cfm?tid=201923&tclass=Non%20Public%20-%20%20A 2007 Girls Team Swimming - Non Public - A], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed July 22, 2007.</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the boys' basketball team brought home the school's first Cape Atlantic League championship after defeating their rival [[Atlantic City High School]], finishing the season with a record of 26-3.<ref>Burrows, Walt. [https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courierpostonline/access/1771204291.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+26%2C+2006&author=WALT+BURROWS&pub=Courier+Post&desc=Spiller's+tip-in+lifts+Holy+Spirit&pqatl=google \"Spiller's tip-in lifts Holy Spirit\"], ''[[Courier-Post]]'', February 26, 2006. Accessed July 10, 2011. \"Cliff Spiller was in an unfamiliar role Saturday when he scored the winning basket and finished with a career-high 13 points in leading Holy Spirit High School to its first-ever Cape-Atlantic League overall boys' basketball championship. \"</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the girls' soccer team won their first Cape Atlantic League championship, beating [[Ocean City High School]] 4\u20131, after having lost in the league's title game in each of the four previous years.<ref>McCann, Courtney. [http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AC&p_theme=ac&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1062730792DD7EE8&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM \"Girls High School Soccer Cape Atlantic League Championships / Spirit Upsets Ocean City\"], ''[[The Press of Atlantic City]]'', November 3, 2004. Accessed September 10, 2012. \"It may have taken four years, but the Holy Spirit High School girls soccer team finally got what it came for. The Spartans upset Ocean City 4-1 to win the Cape-Atlantic League Championship on Tuesday.\"</ref>\n\nThe 2007 girls' tennis team took the South A state sectional championship with a 3\u20132 win over [[Notre Dame High School (New Jersey)|Notre Dame High School]] in the tournament final.<ref>[http://www.bracketmaker.com/tmenu.cfm?tid=242871&tclass=South%20A 2007 Girls Team Tennis - South A], [[New Jersey State Interscholastic Athletic Association]]. Accessed October 26, 2007.</ref>\n\nThe baseball team finished the season with a 14\u201316 record, winning the South Jersey Non-Public final by a score of 7\u20131 against [[Marist High School (New Jersey)|Marist High School]] and then won the Non-Public B state championship for the first time since 1982 with a 9\u20134 win against [[Newark Academy]].<ref>McGarry, Michael. [http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/sports/local/highschool/holy-spirit-baseball-wins-first-state-title-in-years/article_894f41de-0c8c-11e5-96ce-5f4c9ef305e0.html \"Holy Spirit baseball wins first state title in 33 years\"], ''[[The Press of Atlantic City]]'', June 6, 2015. Accessed May 26, 2016. \"The Spartans capped their memorable playoff run by beating Newark Academy 9-4 to win the state Non-Public B title at Toms River North on Saturday afternoon.... The win gave Spirit its first state baseball title since 1982..\"</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the girls' soccer team won the South Jersey Non-Public B final against [[Our Lady of Mercy Academy (New Jersey)|Our Lady of Mercy Academy]] 4\u20131 after losing the previous year to Moorestown Friends. This was the first time Spartan girls' soccer has won this title and the first time the team went to the New Jersey Non-Public B state final.<ref>Gould, Brandon. [http://highschoolsports.nj.com/news/article/-4582336301425343878/girls-soccer-2016-non-public-b-state-final-preview-holy-spirit-vs-morris-catholic/ \"Girls Soccer: 2016 Non-Public B final preview - Holy Spirit vs. Morris Catholic\"], NJ Advance Media for [[NJ.com]], November 11, 2016. Accessed January 10, 2017. \"Holy Spirit made school history on Thursday with a 4-1 victory over Our Lady of Mercy in the South Jersey, Non-Public B final. Christine Conaghy scored three times in the final to lift the fifth-seeded South Jersey squad to its first ever sectional title.\"</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{Category see also|Holy Spirit High School alumni}}\n* [[Joe Callahan (American football)|Joe Callahan]] (born 1993), football quarterback who played for the [[Green Bay Packers]].<ref>Clements, Ron. [http://www.sportingnews.com/nfl/news/joe-callahan-green-bay-rookie-quarterback-hall-of-fame-game/cyylqey8s8gg1s0kkxjhv4mgt \"Who is Joe Callahan? Get to know the Packers rookie QB\"], ''[[Sporting News]]'', August 7, 2016. Accessed October 2, 2017. \"Callahan, whose full name is Francis Joseph, was born and raised in Absecon, N.J., where he was a standout player at Holy Spirit High School.\"</ref>\n* [[John F. Duffy]] (born 1963), legal commentator and author, Professor of Law at the [[University of Virginia School of Law]].{{citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n* [[Chris Ford]] (born 1949), pro-basketball player, head coach.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=1731658 \"Assistant Ford promoted to replace Ayers\"], [[ESPN.com]], February 10, 2004. Accessed May 21, 2007. \"A native of Atlantic City, N.J., Ford attended Holy Spirit High School in Absecon, N.J., and went on to play at Villanova University from 1968-72, where he helped the Wildcats reach the 1971 NCAA championship game against UCLA.\"</ref>\n* [[William Green (American football)|William Green]] (born 1979), [[running back]] who currently is a [[free agent]] of the [[National Football League|NFL]].<ref>[http://www.nflplayers.com/players/player.aspx?id=32992 William Green player profile], [[National Football League Players Association]]. Accessed July 23, 2007. \"Hometown: Atlantic City, NJ... Earned All-America honors from Super Prep, Tom Lemming, National Recruiting Advisor, RivalNet, Prep Star, Parade and Blue Chip Illustrated and was rated among Super Prep's National Top 50 (third-rated running back on the magazine's dream team), in addition to being a consensus all-state selection at Holy Spirit (Atlantic City, N.J.) High School.\"</ref>\n* [[Dennis Horner]] (born 1988), basketball player who played for the [[NBA]]'s [[New Jersey Nets]].<ref>[http://www.nj.com/nets/index.ssf/2011/12/nets_finalize_roster_by_waivin.html Nets finalize roster by waiving Ime Udoka, keeping Linwood native Dennis Horner] By Jorge Castillo, The Star-Ledger of Newark, December 23, 2011</ref>\n* [[Brian Joo]] (born 1981), of [[Fly to the Sky]], American R&B and South Korean pop (a.k.a. K-pop) recording artist and entertainer who is based in the United States and South Korea.<ref>Eisenlohr, Scott. [http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AC&p_theme=ac&p_action=search&p_maxdoc