 Boulder | last=Stephens | first=Josh | work=[[Next City]] | date=2016-06-21 | accessdate=2018-07-31 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915031437/https://nextcity.org/daily/entry/who-are-yimby-first-meeting-boulder | archive-date=2016-09-15 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n<ref name=SFC_Yelp_CEO >{{cite news | url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/business/networth/article/Yelp-CEO-calls-on-Google-Facebook-to-help-12849616.php | title=Yelp CEO calls on Google, Facebook to help housing crisis | last=Pender | first=Kathleen | newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] | date=2018-04-19 | accessdate=2018-06-06 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180428055620/https://www.sfchronicle.com/business/networth/article/Yelp-CEO-calls-on-Google-Facebook-to-help-12849616.php | archive-date=2018-04-28 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n<ref name=SJMN_Stripe >{{cite news | url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2018/05/03/pro-development-yimby-group-scores-1-million-from-stripe-tackle-housing-shortage/ | title=Stripe gives $1 million to pro-development YIMBY group tackling Bay Area housing shortage | last=Kendall | first=Marisa | newspaper=[[The Mercury News|San Jose Mercury News]] | date=2018-05-03 | accessdate=2018-10-20 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180609150123/https://www.mercurynews.com/2018/05/03/pro-development-yimby-group-scores-1-million-from-stripe-tackle-housing-shortage/ | archive-date=2018-06-09 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n<ref name=NYT_NY-YIMBY >{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/06/realestate/sure-build-it-in-my-backyard.html | title=Sure, Build It in My Backyard | last=Rosenblum | first=Constance | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=2014-04-04 | accessdate=2018-07-03 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020203731/http://www.nytimes.com:80/2014/04/06/realestate/sure-build-it-in-my-backyard.html | archive-date=2014-10-20 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n<ref name=Politico_Fedak >{{ cite web | url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2016/05/nikolai-fedak-city-polemicist-048262 | title=Nikolai Fedak, city polemicist | last=Prakash | first=Nidhi | publisher=[[Politico]] | date=2014-07-29 | accessdate=2018-07-03 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170330005226/http://www.politico.com:80/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2016/05/nikolai-fedak-city-polemicist-048262 | archive-date=2017-03-30 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n<ref name=Curbed_NY_YIMBY >{{ cite news | url=https://ny.curbed.com/2018/9/17/17869546/open-new-york-yimby-rezoning-brooklyn-nimby | title=The YIMBY movement comes to New York City - Open New York, the city's first self-style YIMBY group, advocates for more housing in high-opportunity areas | last=Raskin | first=Sam | publisher=[[Curbed]] | date=September 17, 2018 | accessdate=2019-03-28 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203060005/https://ny.curbed.com/2018/9/17/17869546/open-new-york-yimby-rezoning-brooklyn-nimby | archive-date=2019-02-03 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.dailycamera.com/news/boulder/ci_30031436/yimby-spirit-simmers-boulder-is-set-rule-co \"'YIMBY' spirit simmers as Boulder is set to rule on co-ops\"] in the ''[[Daily Camera]]''\n* [https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/the-san-francisco-activists-who-say-please-build-in-my-backyard/ \"The San Francisco activists who say please build in my backyard\"] on ''[[PBS NewsHour]]''\n* [http://www.yimby.wiki/wiki/YIMBY_organizations_directory \"YIMBY organizations directory\"]\n\n[[Category:Urban studies and planning terminology]]\n[[Category:Environmental sayings]]\n[[Category:Political terminology]]\n", "name_user": "Davemck", "label": "safe", "comment": "rmv duplicate parm", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/YIMBY"}
{"title_page": "Guus Hiddink", "text_new": "Big bulsh{{Redirect|Hiddink|the stadium named after him|Guus Hiddink Stadium}}\n{{short description|Dutch association football player and maganer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Guus Hiddink\n| image               = Guus Hiddink 2012.jpg\n| image_size          = 292\n| caption             = Hiddink in 2012\n| fullname            = Guus Hiddink<ref name=BDFutbol>{{cite web |url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/l/l3059.html |title=Hiddink: Guus Hiddink: Manager |publisher=BDFutbol |accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=y|1946|11|8}}<ref name=BDFutbol/>\n| birth_place         = [[Varsseveld]], Netherlands\n| position            = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthclubs1         = SC Varsseveld\n| youthyears1         =\n| clubs1              = [[De Graafschap]]\n| clubs2              = [[PSV Eindhoven]]\n| years1              = 1967\u20131970\n| years2              = 1970\u20131972\n| caps1               =\n| caps2               = 30\n| totalcaps           = 317\n| goals1              =\n| goals2              = 1<ref name=\"voetbal_profile\">{{cite web | url = http://www.vi.nl/Spelers/Speler/Guus-Hiddink.htm  | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100826061658/http://www.vi.nl/Spelers/Speler/Guus-Hiddink.htm | archivedate = 26 August 2010 | title = Eredivisie statistics&nbsp;\u2013 Guus Hiddink | publisher = Voetbal International| language = Dutch | accessdate=15 April 2009}}</ref>\n| totalgoals          = 16\n| managerclubs1       = [[PSV Eindhoven]]\n| managerclubs2       = [[Fenerbah\u00e7e S.K.|Fenerbah\u00e7e]]\n| manageryears1       = 1987\u20131990\n| manageryears2       = 1990\u20131991\n| years3              = 1972\u20131977\n| years4              = 1977\u20131981\n| years5              = 1978\n| years6              = 1980\n| years7              = 1981\u20131982\n| clubs3              = [[De Graafschap]]\n| clubs4              = [[NEC (football club)|NEC Nijmegen]]\n| clubs5              = \u2192 [[Washington Diplomats]] (loan)\n| clubs6              = \u2192 [[San Jose Earthquakes (1974\u201388)|San Jose Earthquakes]] (loan)\n| clubs7              = [[De Graafschap]]\n| caps3               = 130\n| goals3              = 9<ref name=\"voetbal_profile\"/>\n| caps4               = 104\n| goals4              = 2<ref name=\"voetbal_profile\"/>\n| caps5               = 13\n| goals5              = 4<ref name=\"nasl_profile\">{{cite web| url= http://www.nasljerseys.com/Players/H/Hiddink.Cus.htm | title= NASL Player Profile&nbsp;\u2013 Guus Hiddink| accessdate=24 November 2008}}</ref>\n| caps6               = 15\n| goals6              = 0<ref name=\"nasl_profile\" />\n| caps7               = 25\n| goals7              = 0<ref name=\"voetbal_profile\"/>\n| manageryears3       = 1991\u20131993\n| manageryears4       = 1994\n| manageryears5       = 1995\u20131998\n| manageryears6       = 1998\u20131999\n| manageryears7       = 2000\n| manageryears8       = 2001\u20132002\n| manageryears9       = 2002\u20132006\n| manageryears10       = 2005\u20132006\n| manageryears11      = 2006\u20132010\n| manageryears12      = 2009\n| manageryears13      = 2010\u20132011\n| manageryears14      = 2012\u20132013\n| manageryears15      = 2014\u20132015\n| manageryears16      = 2015\u20132016\n| manageryears17      = 2018\u20132019\n| manageryears18      = 2020\u2013\n| managerclubs3       = [[Valencia CF|Valencia]]\n| managerclubs4       = [[Valencia CF|Valencia]]\n| managerclubs5       = [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]]\n| managerclubs6       = [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]\n| managerclubs7       = [[Real Betis]]\n| managerclubs8       = [[Korea Republic national football team|South Korea]]\n| managerclubs9       = [[PSV Eindhoven]]\n| managerclubs10       = [[Australia national association football team|Australia]]\n| managerclubs11      = [[Russia national football team|Russia]]\n| managerclubs12      = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] (interim)\n| managerclubs13      = [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]]\n| managerclubs14      = [[FC Anzhi Makhachkala|Anzhi Makhachkala]]\n| managerclubs15      = [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]]\n| managerclubs16     = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] (interim)\n| managerclubs17      = [[China national under-23 football team|China U-21/U-23]]\n}}\n\n'''Guus Hiddink''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8\u0263ys \u02c8\u0266\u026ad\u026a\u014bk|-|Nl-Guus Hiddink.ogg}}; born 8 November 1946) is a Dutch [[Association football|football]] manager and former player.He enjoyed a long career playing as a [[midfielder]] in his native [[Netherlands]], playing for sides such as PSV Eindhoven, [[De Graafschap]] and [[NEC (football club)|NEC Nijmegen]], as well as some time spent playing in the United States. Since retiring from playing the game in 1982, Hiddink has gone on to enjoy an illustrious career in management, leading both clubs and countries from across the globe to achieve various titles and feats.\n\nIn March 1987, Hiddink was appointed [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]] manager after previously serving as assistant. Hiddink's PSV side won three consecutive [[Eredivisie]] titles, three consecutive [[KNVB Cup]]s and the [[1987\u201388 European Cup|European Cup]] in the historic [[Treble (association football)|Treble]]-winning season of [[1987\u201388 PSV Eindhoven season|1987\u201388]]. Hiddink spent one unsuccessful season at [[Istanbul]] side [[Fenerbah\u00e7e S.K. (football)|Fenerbah\u00e7e]], then the following season was appointed manager of [[Valencia CF|Valencia]], where he stayed until November 1993. He returned to the [[Mestalla Stadium|Mestalla]] in March 1994, where he stayed for the rest of the [[1993\u201394 La Liga|1993\u201394]] season.\n\nHiddink then took charge of the [[Netherlands national football team|Dutch national team]] in January 1995, leading the Dutch to the quarter-finals of [[UEFA Euro 1996]] and a fourth-place finish in the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]]. He resigned as Netherlands manager after the World Cup, where he was then appointed manager of Spanish giants [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]. His time in [[Madrid]] ended prematurely after he was sacked in February 1999 as Real were struggling in the league. He took over the reins at fellow [[La Liga]] side [[Real Betis]] in February 2000, but was sacked just three months later, following the season's conclusion.\n\nThe lure of taking another team to a World Cup led to Hiddink taking the [[Korea Republic national football team|South Korea national team]] job in January 2001. [[Korea Republic|South Korea]] were joint hosts of the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]], so expectations were high. He led South Korea to a historic 4th-placed finish and became a national hero there.<ref>{{Cite web|title = BBC SPORT {{!}} WORLD CUP {{!}} Results|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/bsp/statistics/results.stm|publisher = BBC|access-date = 14 January 2016}}</ref> Hiddink returned to the Netherlands to rejoin PSV after the conclusion of the World Cup. During his second spell, he won three more Eredivise titles and another KNVB Cup, making him the most successful football manager in Dutch history. In July 2005, Hiddink was appointed manager of the [[Australia national soccer team|Australian national team]], serving as manager of both PSV and Australia simultaneously. He led Australia to qualify for their first World Cup in 32 years, while at the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]] itself, he led the nation to the knockout stages, the first time in the Socceroos' history. Following the World Cup, he joined the [[Russia national football team|Russian national team]]. Russia scraped through qualification at the expense of [[England national football team|England]], ultimately reaching the semi-finals of [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]].\n\nIn February 2009, while still managing Russia, Hiddink was appointed interim manager of English club [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]. He enjoyed success during his short stay at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]], winning the [[FA Cup]], whilst restoring Chelsea to a respectable position in the league. Meanwhile, after Russia failed to qualify for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]], Hiddink resigned as its manager. He returned to Turkey as [[Turkey national football team|Turkish national team]] manager, but his time in charge ended two years later after the nation failed to qualify for [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]]. In February 2012, Hiddink made a return to club management, taking charge of Russian side [[FC Anzhi Makhachkala|Anzhi Makhachkala]]. After a period of relative success, Hiddink left Anzhi in July 2013.\n\nFollowing the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]], Hiddink succeeded [[Louis van Gaal]] as [[Netherlands national football team|Dutch national team]] manager, his second stint in charge of his home nation. His time at the helm ended, however, as the Netherlands were struggling to qualify for [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]]; he was subsequently relieved of his post and replaced by [[Danny Blind]]. Following this, nearly six years after his previous departure from Chelsea, Hiddink was again appointed interim manager of the London-based club in December 2015 following the sacking of [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]].\n\n==Playing career==\nHiddink was born in [[Varsseveld]]<ref name=BDFutbol/> and started his career as a player in the youth side of amateur club SC Varsseveld. He turned professional after signing on for Dutch club [[De Graafschap]] in 1967. Hiddink played at the [[Doetinchem]] club under manager [[Piet de Visser (football manager)|Piet de Visser]]. In 1973, Hiddink and manager de Visser earned promotion to the [[Eredivisie]], the top league in Dutch football.<ref>{{cite news|title=Oeuvreprijs naar Piet de Visser |url=http://www.net2client.com/ZZZ/08/04101/Uitslagen_2004.htm?MCT7evlngrp3%C3%BE |publisher=Rinus Michels Awards 2005 |date=28 May 2005 |accessdate=17 January 2007 |language=Dutch |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20070928064135/http://www.net2client.com/ZZZ/08/04101/Uitslagen_2004.htm?MCT7evlngrp3%C3%BE |archivedate=28 September 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Ever since, the careers of the two Dutchmen have intersected: De Visser scouted numerous South American players, such as PSV players [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]], [[Rom\u00e1rio]] (who played under Hiddink at PSV from 1988 until 1990) and former Chelsea defender [[Alex Rodrigo Dias da Costa|Alex]], for Hiddink's PSV. Also, De Visser, in his role as personal advisor to [[Roman Abramovich]], was influential in bringing Hiddink to the [[Russia national football team]] and more recently to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] as caretaker manager following the dismissal of Brazilian [[Luiz Felipe Scolari]]. It was De Visser who introduced Hiddink to Abramovich during a meeting in [[Eindhoven]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite news | title=Will the Kremlin demand the final say in Hiddink's future at Chelsea?| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1145538/Will-Kremlin-demand-final-say-Hiddinks-future-Chelsea.html | newspaper=Daily Mail | date=14 February 2009 | accessdate=14 February 2009 | location=London | first=Rob | last=Draper}}</ref> He spent most of his playing career at De Graafschap, including three years under de Visser, and remains a fan of the club. He joined [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]] in 1970, but after failing to win a permanent position in the team, he rejoined De Graafschap after just one year and remained there until 1977. In 1981, he rejoined De Graafschap and retired a year later. He generally played as a [[Midfielder (association football)|midfielder]] during his playing days.\n\n==Managerial career==\n\n===Early club career===\n{{multiple image | direction = vertical | width = 220\n|image1=Ajax tegen PSV 2-0 trainer Guus Hiddink , kop, Bestanddeelnr 934-3348.jpg\n|caption1=Guus Hiddink in 1988 as manager of [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]].\n|image2=Aankomst PSV met Europa Cup I op vliegveld Eindhoven Hans van Breukelen en trai, Bestanddeelnr 934-2544.jpg\n|caption2=Hiddink (right) and [[Hans van Breukelen]] (left) holding the European Cup on arrival at [[Eindhoven Airport]]\n}}\nHaving honed his coaching skills as an assistant manager, Hiddink took over the managerial role at [[PSV Eindhoven]] in 1987 after also holding the assistant manager position for the club from 1983 to March 1987. Hiddink took over in March 1987, whilst the team was trailing by three points behind [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] with ten matches remaining in the [[1986\u201387 Eredivisie|league]]. PSV, however, managed to win the championship six points ahead of Ajax. It was at PSV where he led the team to its first ever [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] triumph in 1988 (and [[The Treble]]), affirming the Eindhoven club's ranking as one of the three giants of Dutch football, alongside rivals Ajax and [[Feyenoord]]. He also won three [[Eredivisie]] titles with the club in between 1987 and 1990. \"Hiddink will never take all the credit for himself, he will also involve his staff in it. That adds to the strong sense of unity. Hiddink has final responsibility, but always shares it with the team around him. He is a real team player,\" said [[Berry van Aerle]], who was coached by Hiddink in two separate periods with PSV.<ref>\n{{Cite news\n| url        = http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=418237.html\n| title      = Van Aerle about Hiddink: \"He is a real team player\"\n| work       = Berend Scholten @ UEFA.com\n| date       = 5 May 2006\n}}\n</ref>\n\nHiddink also had a coaching stint at Turkish club [[Fenerbah\u00e7e S.K. (football)|Fenerbah\u00e7e]] in 1990, but was dismissed after one year, later joining Spanish giants [[Valencia CF|Valencia]].<ref>{{Cite news\n| url        = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/guus-hiddink-flying-dutchman-1670444.html\n| title      = Guus Hiddink: Flying Dutchman\n| work       = [[The Independent]]\n| date       = 18 April 2009\n| accessdate =1 May 2009\n| location=London\n| first=Brian\n| last=Viner\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Dutch national team===\nHiddink would face his biggest managerial challenge when he took over the reins of the [[Netherlands national football team|Dutch national team]] on 1 January 1995,<ref name=dutchjob>\n{{Cite news\n| url        = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9401E6DF1038F933A15751C1A962958260\n| title      = Soccer Report\n| work       = [[The New York Times]]\n| date       = 20 December 1994\n| accessdate =20 September 2008\n| first=Alex\n| last=Yannis\n}}\n</ref> where he took charge of a team of talented individuals continually racked by internal arguments and disputes. His usual [[Formation (association football)#4\u20134\u20132|4\u20134\u20132]] tactic of deploying wingers backed-up by central midfielders resulted in goals from defensive midfielders such as [[Philip Cocu]] and [[Edgar Davids]]. Hiddink took a firm approach to the team, an example of which was demonstrated at [[UEFA Euro 1996]] when Edgar Davids was sent home after an argument with Hiddink.<ref>\n{{Cite news\n| url        = http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/world/events/1998/worldcup/news/1998/06/29/91st_minute/\n| title      = Davids matures, sends Dutch to quarters\n| work       = [[Sports Illustrated]]\n| date       = 29 June 1998\n| accessdate =20 September 2008\n}}\n</ref><ref name=\"nyt_davids_redemption\">\n{{Cite news\n| url        = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9901EFDC133FF933A05755C0A96E958260\n| title      = Netherlands' Davids Comes in From Cold\n| work       = [[The New York Times]]\n| date       = 30 June 1998\n| accessdate =7 October 2008\n| first=Roger\n| last=Cohen\n}}\n</ref>\nHe was able to prevent further internal conflict in the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]]<ref name=\"nyt_davids_redemption\" /> where his team played some of the more entertaining football in that tournament.<ref>{{Cite news\n| url        = http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1013331/index.htm\n| title      = Soccer:Orange Blossom\n| work       = [[Sports Illustrated]]\n| date       = 13 July 1998\n| accessdate =7 October 2008\n}}\n</ref>\nThe team beat [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] in the quarter-finals 2\u20131, then suffered a defeat at the hands of [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] on penalties in the semi-final. This loss signalled an end of another era for Hiddink, as he resigned as Dutch national coach soon after.\n\n===Real Madrid and Real Betis===\nHiddink became manager of Spanish [[La Liga]] side [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] in the summer of 1998, replacing [[Jupp Heynckes]], but poor league form and off-pitch remarks about the board and finances of the club prompted his termination in February 1999.<ref>\n{{Cite news\n| url        = http://www.elmundo.es/1999/02/02/deportes/2N0124.html\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100213191016/http://www.elmundo.es/1999/02/02/deportes/2N0124.html\n| archivedate=13 February 2010\n| title      = Lorenzo Sanz: \"If he said it, he'll be gone in five minutes\"\n| work       = El Mundo\n| date       = 2 February 1999\n| accessdate =20 September 2008\n|language=es}}\n</ref><ref>\n{{Cite news\n| url        = http://www.elmundo.es/1999/01/28/deportes/28N0099.html\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20020817023353/http://www.elmundo.es/1999/01/28/deportes/28N0099.html\n| archivedate= 17 August 2002\n| title      = Hiddink to Sanz: \"This club has to be much more professional\"\n| work       = El Mundo\n| date       = 28 January 1999\n| accessdate = 20 September 2008\n|language=es}}\n</ref> Hiddink then took over the reins at Spanish club [[Real Betis]] in 2000 for the rest of the season. His time at Real Betis would end badly, with Hiddink being sacked by May 2000.<ref name=\"rte_fired\">\n{{Cite news\n| url        = http://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/2000/0502/scottish1.html\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110605134439/http://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/2000/0502/scottish1.html\n| archivedate= 5 June 2011\n| title      = Guus Hiddink has been sacked by Real Betis\n| publisher       = [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]]\n| date       = 2 May 2000\n| accessdate =20 September 2008\n}}\n</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2000, rumours were rife over his future, with Scottish club [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] among one of the clubs named as a potential destination.<ref name=\"rte_fired\" /> The temptation to manage another World Cup-bound international team proved irresistible to him, however, as he agreed to coach the [[Korea Republic national football team|South Korean national football team]] on 1 January 2001.\n\n===South Korea===\nHiddink became manager of South Korea in January 2001.<ref name=southkoreajob>{{cite news|title=Hiddink to lead South Korea|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2002/1060755.stm|accessdate=8 March 2013|publisher=BBC Sport|date=8 December 2000}}</ref> Success would not come easily with a team that had appeared in five-straight World Cups but had yet to win a single match. South Korea was one of the host nations for the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]] tournament, along with Japan. There was an expectation that the hosts would progress to the second round of the tournament and it was clearly expressed that Hiddink's team was expected to perform to that standard as well.<ref name=\"nyt_sk_savior\">{{Cite news\n| url        = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9904E2D7123FF932A15755C0A9649C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all\n| title      = South Koreans' Savior Is Found in Dutchman\n| work       = [[The New York Times]]\n| date       = 21 June 2002\n| accessdate = 1 October 2008\n| first=Jere\n| last=Longman\n}}\n</ref>\n[[File:2004 guuseum.jpg|thumb|right|''Guuseum'' in [[Varsseveld]]. \ud788\ub529\ud06c \ubc15\ubb3c\uad00 in [[Korean language|Korean]]]]\n\nHiddink's first year in charge was not met with favourable reviews from the South Korean press,<ref name=\"nyt_sk_savior\" /> as he was often spotted together with his girlfriend when some felt<ref name=\"nyt_sk_savior\" /> he should instead have been taking charge of the team. After a 2\u20131 loss to the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] [[CONCACAF Gold Cup|Gold Cup]] team in January 2002, he was criticized again for not taking his job seriously.<ref name=\"nyt_sk_savior\" /> Nevertheless, the team he assembled was a cohesive unit. However, Hiddink began focusing on physical fitness for players during training in preparation for the World Cup later that year.\n\nIn the World Cup itself, the South Korean team achieved its first ever victory in the first stage (2\u20130, against [[Poland national football team|Poland]]), and after a 1\u20131 draw with the U.S. and a further 1\u20130 victory against heavily favoured [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], the South Korean team qualified for the second round.\n\nTheir second round opponents were [[Italy national football team|Italy]], who they defeated 2\u20131 on the golden goal rule. The Korean public then began to dream of a semi-final berth, a dream that was realized after defeating [[Spain national football team|Spain]] on penalties in the quarter-final. This surpassed the record of their [[North Korea national football team|North Korean]] counterparts 36 years before, who had beaten [[Italy national football team|Italy]] to reach the quarter-finals.\n\nThe South Korean team's run was halted by [[Germany national football team|Germany]], managed by [[Rudi V\u00f6ller]], in the semi-finals. As with the Netherlands team four years before in France, Hiddink led his team into fourth place after a 2-3 defeat to [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] in the third-place playoff.\n\nPrior to the tournament, football pundits and fans alike never expected this level of success. Many in South Korea were overjoyed when the country reached the semi-finals of the 2002 World Cup.<ref name=\"nyt_sk_savior\" />\nHiddink became the first-ever person to be given [[Honorary Citizen of South Korea|honorary South Korean citizenship]].<ref>{{Cite news\n| url        = http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/news/2002/07/03/hiddink_psv\n| title      = Honorary Citizenship\n| work       = [[Sports Illustrated]]\n| date       = 3 July 2002\n| accessdate =7 October 2008\n}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt_sk_rewards\" /> In addition, other rewards soon followed&nbsp;\u2014 a private villa in [[Jeju-do]] island;<ref name=\"nyt_sk_rewards\" /> free flights for life with [[Korean Air]] and [[Asiana Airlines]], free [[taxicab|taxi]] rides, among others.<ref name=\"nyt_sk_rewards\">{{Cite news\n| url        = https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/21/sports/soccer/21coaches.html?_r=1&oref=slogin&pagewanted=all\n| title      = A Little Traveling Music: Some Coaches Get Around\n| work       = [[The New York Times]]\n| date       = 21 June 2006\n| accessdate =7 October 2008\n| first=Jere\n| last=Longman\n}}\n</ref> The World Cup stadium in [[Gwangju]], where South Korea qualified for the semi-finals, was renamed [[Guus Hiddink Stadium]] in his honour shortly after the tournament.<ref>{{cite web | title = Russia: A new hope | author = Dale Johnson | date=29 May 2008 | publisher = ESPN | url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=539119&&cc=3888 | accessdate =3 July 2008}}</ref> His hometown, where a ''Guuseum'' was set up, became a popular stopover for South Koreans visiting the Netherlands. The ''Guuseum'' is a ''museum'' established by his relatives, in [[Varsseveld]], to honor Hiddink.\n\n===PSV===\nHiddink chose to return to his native country and took over the coaching duties at [[PSV Eindhoven]] in 2002.<ref name=psvreturn>{{Cite news\n| url        = http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/news/2002/07/08/hiddink_eindhoven/| title      = Hiddink returns to Holland after wonderous World Cup run| work       = [[Sports Illustrated]]| date       = 8 July 2002| accessdate =7 October 2008}}\n</ref> During his second spell with PSV, Hiddink won three [[Eredivisie|Dutch league titles]] ([[2002\u201303 Eredivisie|2002\u201303]], [[2004\u201305 Eredivisie|2004\u201305]], and [[2005\u201306 Eredivisie|2005\u201306]]), the 2005 [[KNVB Cup|Dutch Cup]] and the 2003 [[Johan Cruijff Shield|Dutch Super Cup]]. In Europe, the [[2004\u201305 UEFA Champions League|2004\u201305]] [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] led to PSV's first ever appearance in the semi-final of the tournament since it adopted its current format in 1992\u201393 (PSV won the European Cup, the predecessor to the modern Champions League, in 1988, with Hiddink as coach). PSV narrowly lost the semi-final to [[A.C. Milan|Milan]], on [[Away goals rule|away goals]].\n\nIn the [[2005\u201306 UEFA Champions League|2005\u201306 Champions League season]], PSV made it through the group stage, but was eliminated in the first knockout round, having lost five of its starting 11 ([[Park Ji-sung]] to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], [[Lee Young-pyo]] to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], [[Mark van Bommel]] to [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], [[Johann Vogel]] to Milan and [[Wilfred Bouma]] to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]) to transfers. This period at PSV would make Hiddink the most successful Dutch coach in history,<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.psv.nl/News/News-page/Guus-Hiddink-most-successful-coach.htm\n |title       = Guus Hiddink most successful coach\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140512221602/http://www.psv.nl/News/News-page/Guus-Hiddink-most-successful-coach.htm\n |archivedate = 12 May 2014\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref> with six Dutch League titles and four Dutch Cups, surpassing the record of [[Rinus Michels]]. Hiddink left the club in June 2006.<ref name=psvresignation>{{cite news|title=England still an option as Hiddink leaves PSV|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/mar/25/newsstory.psveindhoven|accessdate=8 March 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=25 March 2006|author=Jon Brodkin|author2=Marcus Christenson|author3=Matt Scott}}</ref>\n\n===Australia===\nOn 22 July 2005, Hiddink became manager of the [[Australia national soccer team|Australian national team]].<ref name=australiajob>{{cite news|title=Hiddink gets Australia coach role|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/4669189.stm|accessdate=8 March 2013|publisher=BBC|date=22 July 2005}}</ref> He announced he would manage both PSV and Australia at the same time.<ref name=australiajob/>\n\nIn the [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (play-off CONMEBOL-OFC)|play-offs]] held with [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] in Montevideo on 12 November and in Sydney on 16 November 2005, both home teams won 1\u20130. Australia went on to win 4\u20132 on penalties<ref name=\"nyt_wc2006\">{{Cite news| url        = https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/17/sports/soccer/17soccer.html| title      = On to Germany: Final Five World Cup Berths Settled| work       = [[The New York Times]]| date       = 17 November 2005| accessdate =7 October 2008}}\n</ref>&nbsp;\u2014 the first time Australia had qualified for the finals in 32 years, and the first time that any team had qualified through winning a penalty shoot-out.\n\nHiddink was a popular figure in Australia and was referred to affectionately as \"Aussie Guus.\" A telling example of the public affection for him was the Socceroo fans chant of \"Goooooooooooos!\" during moments of play. Slogans for the Socceroos' 2006 World Cup campaign were \"No Guus, No Glory,\" \"Guus for P.M.\" and \"In Guus We Trust,\" as well as the play on words of the famous taunt \"Guus your Daddy?\". During the World Cup, a Sydney newspaper started a humorous campaign to lure him away from Russia by proposing a national \"Guus tax\" to pay his wages.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/guus-tough-love-turned-russia-212000464--sow.html|title=Guus' tough love turned Russia around|date=25 June 2008|work=Yahoo Sports}}</ref> More seriously, his reputation was enhanced by his transformation of the national side, with pundits focusing on the improvement to Australia's defence. He is credited with turning a team which conceded many goals under [[Frank Farina]] into a solid defensive unit which only conceded one goal away from home to both Uruguay and the Netherlands. Hiddink's assistants at Australia were Dutch legend [[Johan Neeskens]] and former Australian international [[Graham Arnold]].\n\nThe Socceroos defeated [[Japan national football team|Japan]] 3\u20131 during their first game in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup final stages]], with [[Tim Cahill]] scoring two goals (84', 89') and [[John Aloisi]] scoring one (92') all in the last eight minutes to claim their first World Cup goals and victory ever.<ref>{{Cite news\n| url        = http://www.espnfc.com/uk/en/report/191929/report.html\n| title      = Australia 3 \u2013 1 Japan\n| publisher       = [[ESPN]]\n| date       = 12 June 2006\n| accessdate =12 May 2014\n}}\n</ref> An early controversial<ref>{{Cite news\n| url        = http://www.theage.com.au/news/aussie-update/referee-apologises-to-schwarzer-for-error/2006/06/13/1149964535252.html\n| title      = Referee apologises to Schwarzer for error\n| work       = [[The Age]]\n| date       = 13 June 2006\n| accessdate =7 October 2008\n| location=Melbourne\n| first1=Matthew\n| last1=Hall\n}}\n</ref> call by the Egyptian referee that awarded a goal to the Japanese team, despite an apparent foul to Australian goalkeeper [[Mark Schwarzer]], had the Australians playing catch up until the last eight minutes. After scoring the first goal, Cahill was lucky to get away with a potential foul when he tripped Japan's [[Y\u016bichi Komano]], who had dribbled into the Australian penalty area. The referee missed the incident, and Cahill then broke to score the second on the counter. FIFA's spokesman for refereeing Andreas Werz said that while Japan's first goal was irregular, Egyptian referee Essam Abdel Fatah should also have given Japan a penalty.<ref>{{Cite news\n| url        = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/jun/15/worldcup2006.sport12\n| title      = Japan were robbed by referee, admits Fifa official\n| work       = [[The Guardian]]\n| date       = 15 June 2006\n| accessdate =7 October 2008\n| location=London\n}}\n</ref>\n\nAustralia followed the match against Japan with a 2\u20130 loss to Brazil, leaving the Socceroos needed at least a draw against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] in their last group match to qualify for the knockout stages for the first time in its history. After a match fraught with controversy and erroneous decisions from referee [[Graham Poll]], including an unprecedented three yellow cards given to the same Croatian player, ironically the Australian-born [[Josip \u0160imuni\u0107]], the game ended 2\u20132, and the Socceroos had their draw thanks to a goal from [[Harry Kewell]] to level the game with minutes to spare.\n\nIn the second round, [[Italy national football team|Italy]] beat Australia 1\u20130. After controversially sending off Italian defender [[Marco Materazzi]] in the 55th minute, Spanish referee [[Luis Medina Cantalejo]] awarded Italy's [[Fabio Grosso]] a controversial penalty kick eight seconds from the end of normal time, which was converted by [[Francesco Totti]]. This put Australia out of the World Cup, marking the official end of Hiddink's tenure as Australia's national coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/world-cup-2006/a-beautiful-mind/2005/12/16/1134703612062.html|title=A beautiful mind|work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\n===Russia===\n[[File:Hiddink Euro 2008.jpg|thumb|Hiddink managing the [[Russia national football team|Russian national team]]]]\n\nOn 10 April 2006, Hiddink announced on Dutch television that he would take over as manager of the [[Russia national football team|Russian national team]].<ref name=russiajob>{{cite news|title=Hiddink neuer Coach Russlands|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/intligen/startseite/330764/artikel_hiddink-neuer-coach-russlands.html|accessdate=8 March 2013|newspaper=kicker|date=11 April 2006|language=German}}</ref> He signed a 2-year contract in April 2006 worth \u20ac2&nbsp;million a year.<ref name=russiajob/> His duties for Russia started after managing Australia during the 2006 World Cup.<ref name=russiajob/>\n\nRussia's [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying|Euro 2008 qualification]] hopes came into question after a 2\u20131 loss to [[Israel national football team|Israel]]. However, after a win against [[Andorra national football team|Andorra]], and [[England national football team|England]] losing out to Croatia on the last match day, Russia and Hiddink secured qualification for the final stages of [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]]. At the tournament, the Russians managed to reach the semi-finals with victories against the Netherlands in the quarter-finals<ref>{{Cite news\n| url        = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=990CE7D7133CF931A15755C0A96E9C8B63\n| title      = Russia is Surprise Semi-finalist\n| work       = [[The New York Times]]\n| date       = 22 June 2008\n| accessdate =7 October 2008\n}}\n</ref> and defending champions [[Greece national football team|Greece]] in the group stage.<ref>[[UEFA Euro 2008 Group D]]</ref>\n\n[[Piet de Visser (football manager)|Piet de Visser]], a former head scout of Hiddink's club [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]] and now a personal assistant to [[Roman Abramovich]] at [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], recommended Hiddink to the Chelsea owner, following the departure of [[Avram Grant]] at the end of the [[2007\u201308 Premier League]] season.<ref>{{Cite news\n| url        = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/feb/14/premier-league-chelsea-guus-hiddink-russia\n| title      = How Hiddink adapted 'total football' to achieve global success\n| first      = Jamie\n| last       = Jackson\n| work       = The Guardian\n| date       = 13 February 2009\n| accessdate = 12 May 2014\n}}\n</ref><ref>{{Cite news\n| url        = http://www.espnfc.com/news/story?id=538645&cc=5739\n| title      = Contenders queue up to replace Grant at Blues\n| work       = ESPN Soccernet\n| date       = 24 May 2008\n| accessdate = 12 May 2014\n}}\n</ref> In March 2008, however, Hiddink had already chosen to exercise the two-year extension with Russia, keeping him in the national team's head coaching role until 2010.<ref>{{Cite web\n| title      = Hiddink pens new Russia deal\n| url        = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,12010_3344674,00.html\n| work       = Sky Sports\n| accessdate =25 March 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2009, Russia was defeated by [[Slovenia national football team|Slovenia]] in a [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification|2010 World Cup qualifying play-off]], casting doubt on future ambitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=700532&sec=worldcup2010&cc=5739|title=Hiddink tight-lipped on future|date=19 November 2009|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=19 November 2009}}</ref> On 13 February 2010, it was confirmed that Hiddink would leave the position when his contract expired on 30 June.<ref name=hiddinkleavesrussia>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=740896&sec=europe&cc=4716|title=Guus Hiddink confirms departure from Russia post|date=13 February 2010|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=13 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Chelsea===\nAfter the sacking of [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]'s manager, the Brazilian [[Luiz Felipe Scolari]], during the [[2008\u201309 Premier League]] season, Chelsea confirmed on 11 February 2009 that Hiddink would become Scolari's replacement until the end of the season, whilst continuing his duties with Russia.<ref name=chelseafcjob>{{cite news\n| title      = Chelsea confirm Hiddink as coach\n| url        = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/7882667.stm\n| work  = [[BBC Sport]]\n| date       = 11 February 2009\n| accessdate =11 February 2009\n}}</ref> Hiddink's first game in charge was a 0\u20131 away victory against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] at [[Villa Park]].<ref>{{cite news\n| url        = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7885820.stm\n| title      =  Aston Villa 0\u20131 Chelsea\n| first      = Phil\n| last       = McNulty\n| publisher  = [[BBC News]]\n| date       = 21 February 2009\n| accessdate =27 February 2009\n}}</ref> His first game in charge at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] was a 1\u20130 victory over [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in the [[UEFA Champions League 2008\u201309#First knockout round|Champions League knockout stage]].<ref>{{cite news\n| url        = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7899584.stm\n| title      = Chelsea 1\u20130 Juventus\n| work  = [[BBC Sport]]\n| date       = 25 February 2009\n| accessdate =27 February 2009\n| first=Phil\n| last=McNulty\n}}</ref> Success continued in the form of a 1\u20133 away victory against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\u2014commentators stated that Hiddink had rejuvenated Chelsea following Scolari's departure.<ref>McNulty, Phil (8 April 2009) [http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7977013.stm Liverpool 1\u20133 Chelsea] [[BBC Sport]] Retrieved on 9 April 2009</ref><ref>Kay, Oliver (9 April 2009) [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/european_football/article6062954.ece Liverpool left on ropes by Hiddink's mastery] ''[[The Times]]''. Retrieved 9 April 2009</ref> After knocking Liverpool out of the competition, Hiddink went on to take Chelsea to the semi-finals of the [[2008\u201309 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], where the club was eliminated on the away goals rule to eventual winners [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]; a 93rd minute Bar\u00e7a goal in a 1\u20131 controversial draw at Stamford Bridge, preceded by a 0\u20130 at [[Camp Nou]], sealed Chelsea's fate.<ref>{{cite news\n| url        = http://www.skysports.com/football/match_report/0,19764,11668_3132607,00.html\n| title      = Chelsea 1 \u2013 1 Barcelona\n| first      = Chris\n| last       = Burton\n| publisher  = [[Sky Sports News]]\n| date       = 6 May 2009\n| accessdate =18 May 2009\n}}</ref>\n\nHiddink only lost once during his tenure as Chelsea manager, a 1\u20130 loss to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] at [[White Hart Lane]], where [[Luka Modri\u0107]] scored the only goal of the match. As it turned out, even winning every league game in charge would not have been enough to see Hiddink secure the Premier League title. In the final home game of the season, in which Chelsea beat [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] 2\u20130, Chelsea home fans chanted Hiddink's name throughout the match and called for Chelsea owner [[Roman Abramovich]] to \"sign him up\" on a permanent basis.<ref>{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.chelseafc.com/news-article/article/1660824\n |title       = After The Whistle: Songs of Praise\n |publisher   = Chelsea F.C.\n |date        = 18 May 2009\n |accessdate  = 12 May 2014\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140619172649/http://www.chelseafc.com/news-article/article/1660824\n |archivedate = 19 June 2014\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> Hiddink's highly positive reception highlighted the Chelsea fans' appreciation of the manager. He marked an end to his [[Premier League]] campaign with a thrilling 3\u20132 away win over [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]].\n\nIn his last game as interim coach of Chelsea, he won the 2009 [[FA Cup]] by beating [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] 2\u20131 at [[Wembley Stadium|Wembley]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/article-1189787/Magician-Hiddink-rewarded-spell-absolute-brilliance.html|title=Magician Hiddink rewarded for a spell of absolute brilliance|date=30 May 2009|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=30 May 2009 | location=London | first=Patrick | last=Collins}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premier_league/chelsea/article6394538.ece|title=Frank Lampard hands Guus Hiddink perfect parting gift|date=30 May 2009|work=The Times|accessdate=30 May 2009 | location=London | first=Jonathan | last=Northcroft}}</ref>\nHe was visibly pleased at winning the Cup, and in subsequent interviews claimed it was one of his biggest achievements. Even though throughout his tenure at Chelsea various players asked him to stay, including captain [[John Terry]], [[Michael Ballack]] and [[Petr \u010cech]], Hiddink always stated that he intended to return to his post with Russia. As a parting gift, the Chelsea players gave him an engraved watch and a shirt signed by all of the players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/fa-cup/2009/06/01/chelsea-players-spend-20-000-on-going-away-present-for-guus-hiddink-115875-21405870/|title=Chelsea players spend \u00a320,000 on going-away present for Guus Hiddink |date=1 June 2009|work=The Mirror|accessdate=3 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Turkey===\nOn 16 February 2010, [[Turkish Football Federation]] President [[Mahmut \u00d6zgener]] and Hiddink held talks in [[Amsterdam]]. Hiddink agreed to coach the [[Turkey national football team|Turkish national team]] after his contract with Russia expired on 30 June 2010.<ref name=turkeyjob>{{cite news |title=Guus Hiddink confirmed as Turkey's new manager|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/feb/17/guus-hiddink-turkey-manager |work=The Guardian |date=17 February 2010 |accessdate=17 February 2010}}</ref> His contract with Turkey began on 1 August 2010,<ref name=turkeyjob/> and his staff included assistant manager [[O\u011fuz \u00c7etin]] and goalkeeping coach [[Engin \u0130peko\u011flu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrc.nl/international/article2485410.ece/Guus_Hiddink_to_take_over_as_Turkey_coach|title=Guus Hiddink to take over as Turkey coach|work=NRC Handelsblad}}</ref><ref>{{in lang|nl}} [http://www.nrc.nl/sport/article2485243.ece/Hiddink_wordt_bondscoach_van_Turkije \"Hiddink wordt bondscoach van Turkije\"]</ref>\n\nOn 11 August 2010, Turkey defeated [[Romania national football team|Romania]] 2\u20130 in an international friendly in [[Istanbul]]. [[Emre Bel\u00f6zo\u011flu]] gave Turkey the lead in the 82nd minute after converting a spot kick, followed by [[Arda Turan]] doubling the scoreline after netting from 30 yards out. During his spell as head coach, Hiddink was repeatedly criticized by the media for the size of his salary, for not basing himself in Turkey and intermittently visiting the country for games and preparation camps, and for the alleged fact that he failed to grasp the emotional character of the players and forced them into a cold, rational and overly systematic playing mentality.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}} He resigned after Turkey failed to qualify for [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]] when they lost to [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] 3\u20130 aggregate in the playoffs.<ref name=turkeyresignation>{{cite news|title=Hiddink and Turkey part ways|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=1716681.html|accessdate=7 March 2013|publisher=UEFA|date=16 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Anzhi Makhachkala===\nOn 17 February 2012, Hiddink agreed an 18-month deal to manage Russian club [[FC Anzhi Makhachkala|Anzhi Makhachkala]], his first permanent club post in six years.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/17073674|title=Guus Hiddink named Anzhi Makhachkala manager|date=17 February 2012|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref> In his [[2012\u201313 FC Anzhi Makhachkala season|second season]], he led the team to the bronze medal in the [[2012\u201313 Russian Premier League|Russian Premier League]], and Anzhi made it to the round of 16 of the [[UEFA Europa League]] for the first time. In the quarter-finals of the same competition, having gone down to ten men 55 minutes into the second leg against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], Anzhi came close to going through when [[Mbark Boussoufa]]'s free kick hit the post before [[Papiss Ciss\u00e9]] headed home the winner in the last seconds of the tie, meaning the Magpies won 1\u20130 on aggregate. This was the second time that the English side have knocked out a team managed by Hiddink in the competition, having beaten his PSV side 3\u20132 on aggregate in the quarter-finals of the [[2003\u201304 UEFA Cup|2003\u201304]] season. He announced his retirement at the end of the 2012\u201313 season on 28 November 2012, but later changed his mind.\n\nOn 11 June 2013, Hiddink decided to extend his contract by one more year at Anzhi. Just two games into the [[2013\u201314 Russian Premier League]] season after a 2\u20131 defeat at [[FC Dynamo Moscow|Dynamo Moscow]], however, he unexpectedly resigned on 22 July 2013. He said he left because he completed his mission, which he said was to develop Anzhi in a way that it could progress without him.<ref name=\"BBC Sport\">{{cite web|url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/23411365|title=Guus Hiddink resigns as Anzhi Makhachkala coach|date=22 July 2013|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Dutch national team===\nOn 28 March 2014, it was announced that Hiddink would return to manage the Dutch national team after [[Louis van Gaal]] would step down following the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]]. Hiddink agreed to manage the team up to [[UEFA Euro 2016]], with [[Danny Blind]] and [[Ruud van Nistelrooy]] assisting him and Blind to eventually replace him.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guus Hiddink to replace Louis van Gaal as Netherlands coach|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26784524|accessdate=6 September 2014|publisher=BBC Sport|date=28 March 2014}}</ref> His second spell in charge of the team began with a 2\u20130 defeat to Italy in a friendly on 4 September 2014, with both goals conceded and a red card received within the first ten minutes of the match.<ref>{{cite news|title=Italy 2\u20130 Netherlands|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29047063|accessdate=6 September 2014|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 September 2014}}</ref> Five days later, the Dutch began their [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying]] campaign with a 2\u20131 defeat away to the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Czech Rep. 2\u20131 Netherlands|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29131242|accessdate=9 September 2014|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=9 September 2014}}</ref> a 3\u20131 victory against [[Kazakhstan national football team|Kazakhstan]] and a 2\u20130 defeat in the hands of [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]] a month later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/qualifiers/season=2016/matches/round=2000446/match=2013850/postmatch/quotes/index.html|title=Van Persie and Afellay enjoy Dutch drama|date=11 October 2014|publisher=UEFA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/qualifiers/season=2016/matches/round=2000446/match=2013875/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Sigurdsson helps Iceland take historic Dutch scalp|date=13 October 2014|publisher=UEFA}}</ref>\n\nThe 2015 calendar year began in March with a match against Turkey, ending in a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/qualifiers/season=2016/matches/round=2000446/match=2013929/postmatch/report/|title=Netherlands level late against Turkey|date=28 March 2015|publisher=UEFA}}</ref> On 29 June 2015, Hiddink left his position.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guus Hiddink leaves job as Netherlands coach after 10 months|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/33321836|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=1 July 2015|date=29 June 2015}}</ref> Two days later, he was succeeded by his assistant, Danny Blind.<ref>{{cite news|title=Danny Blind succeeds Guus Hiddink as Netherlands coach|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/33354271|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=1 July 2015|date=1 July 2015}}</ref> It was unknown for a long time whether Hiddink was fired or left his position voluntarily, but on 21 November 2015, he said, whilst on vacation in France, that he was fired from the post.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/sport/hiddink-ontslag-was-complete-overval~a4192123/|date=21 November 2015|title=Hiddink|work=De Volkskrant}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Chelsea===\nOn 19 December 2015, Hiddink was appointed first-team manager of English side [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] until the end of the [[2015\u201316 Chelsea F.C. season|2015\u201316]] season, following the dismissal of [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]]; he joined the club in the same capacity he did back in 2009. After being made interim manager, Hiddink spoke, saying he was \"excited to return to Stamford Bridge\" and \"I am looking forward to working with the players and staff at this great club and especially renewing my wonderful relationship with the Chelsea fans.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news/latest-news/2015/12/hiddink-appointed-.html|title=Hiddink appointed|publisher=Chelsea F.C.|date=19 December 2015|accessdate=19 December 2015}}</ref> After the home draw against [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]], Hiddink set a new record for the longest unbeaten streak as a new manager in the [[Premier League]] with 12 games unbeaten, previously a record held by [[Frank Clark (footballer)|Frank Clark]] with [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] in the 1993\u201394 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3480375/Chelsea-boss-Guus-Hiddink-breaks-Premier-League-record-man-steer-12-games-unbeaten.html|title=Chelsea boss Guus Hiddink breaks Premier League record as he becomes first man to steer side through first 12 games unbeaten|date=7 March 2016|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nChelsea ended the season in tenth place in the [[2015\u201316 Premier League|Premier League]], climbing six positions from 16th upon Hiddink's arrival.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/managers/jose-mourinho/12051070/Jose-Mourinho-sacked-by-Chelsea-live-latest-news.html|title=Jose Mourinho sacked by Chelsea and Guus Hiddink will take over as caretaker manager|date=17 December 2016|work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n===China U-21===\nOn 10 September 2018, Hiddink took over the Chinese under-21 men's team. However, in September 2019, Hiddink was sacked after a string of disappointing results, culminating with a 0\u20132 defeat against [[Vietnam]] under-22 men's team.<ref>https://www.scmp.com/sport/football/article/3029623/dutchman-guus-hiddink-steps-down-after-12-months-charge-china-under</ref> Ironically, the person coaching the Vietnamese team to defeat Hiddink's team was [[Park Hang-seo]], Hiddink's former assistant manager for South Korean team in World Cup 2002.\n\n==Tax evasion==\nIn February 2007, Hiddink was given a six-month suspended jail sentence and fined \u20ac45,000 after being found guilty of tax evasion by a Dutch court. Prosecutors had demanded a ten-month prison sentence for Hiddink, who was accused of evading \u20ac1.4&nbsp;million in Dutch taxes by claiming to be a resident of Belgium from 2002 to 2003. The Dutch Tax Intelligence and Detection Service claimed that he had not spent enough nights at his Belgian house which he had stated was his primary address. Hiddink denied this accusation.<ref>\n{{Cite news\n |title=Hiddink Escapes Jail for Tax Fraud \n |url=http://www.kommersant.com/p745984/r_500/Hiddink_Verdict_Jail_Tax/ \n |work=[[Kommersant]] \n |publisher=Kommersant Publishing House \n |date=28 February 2007 \n |accessdate=23 June 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502133007/http://www.kommersant.com/p745984/r_500/Hiddink_Verdict_Jail_Tax \n |archivedate=2 May 2009 \n}}\n</ref><ref>\n{{Cite news\n| url        = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/feb/27/newsstory.sport14\n| title      = Hiddink found guilty of tax fraud\n| work       = [[The Guardian]]\n| date       = 27 February 2007\n| accessdate =20 September 2008\n| location=London\n| first=Paolo\n| last=Bandini\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|20 September 2019.}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"| From\n!rowspan=\"2\"| To\n!colspan=\"9\"| Record\n|-\n!G\n!W\n!D\n!L\n!GF\n!GA\n!GD\n!Win %\n!Source\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagdeco|NED}} [[PSV Eindhoven]]\n| 16 March 1987<ref name=psvjob>{{cite web|title=PSV Eindhoven .:. Coaches from A-Z|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/teams/psv-eindhoven/9/|publisher=Worldfootball|accessdate=9 March 2013}}</ref>\n| 30 June 1990<ref name=psvjob/>\n{{WDL|153|104|28|21|for=401|against=137|diff=yes}}\n|align=left|<ref>{{cite web|title=Standen|url=http://www.eredivisiestats.nl/standen.php|publisher=eredivisiestats.nl|accessdate=9 March 2013|language=Dutch}}</ref><ref name=\"Ross\">{{cite news|last=Ross|first=James M.|title=European Competitions 1987\u201388|url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec198788.html#sc|accessdate=9 March 2013|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation}}</ref><ref name=\"Ross\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Abbink|first=Dinant|title=Netherlands Cup Full Results 1970\u20131994|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesn/nedcuphistfull.html|accessdate=9 March 2013|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Ross|first=James F.|title=European Competitions 1988\u201389|url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec198889.html|accessdate=9 March 2013|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|date=2 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Ross|first=James M.|title=European Competitions 1989\u201390|url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec198990.html|accessdate=9 March 2013|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Leme de Arruda|first=Marcelo|title=Intercontinental Club Cup 1988|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablest/toyota88.html|accessdate=9 March 2013|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left